"Mos L.","Domoic acid: A fascinating marine toxin",2001,"Environmental Toxicology and Pharmacology","9","3",,"79","85",,,10.1016/S1382-6689(00)00065-X,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035123231&partnerID=40&md5=a673edaa792598e46145c70f9a646e04","Department of Agrotechnology and Food Sciences, Chair Toxicology, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 8000, 6700 EA Wageningen, Netherlands","Mos, L., Department of Agrotechnology and Food Sciences, Chair Toxicology, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 8000, 6700 EA Wageningen, Netherlands","There are indications that toxic algal blooms are increasing because of pollution of coastal waters and worldwide shipping. This mini-review deals with the marine biotoxin domoic acid, also known as amnesic shellfish poison, and its main producing pennate diatom genus Pseudo-nitzschia (Bacillariophyceae). Besides contamination of seafood, these organisms have also been involved in human and marine wildlife mortality. The article aims to give an overview of all biological and environmental factors that should be considered when trying to evaluate a possible increase in toxic blooms of Pseudo-nitzschia spp.. Pseudo-nitzschia blooms characteristically occur in a low light regime, at a time when the temperature is falling and at a wide range of salinities. Laboratory studies have shown that the production of domoic acid, a water-soluble amino acid, is related to silicon, phosphorus, nitrogen and trace metal (mainly iron) availability. Domoic acid has no known function in defence or primary metabolism; a role in excretion of excess photosynthetic energy or as a binding ligand for trace metals is suggested. The variability in domoic acid production by different Pseudo-nitzschia spp., or the presence of toxic and non-toxic strains of the same species, cannot be explained. The conclusion is drawn that an increase in toxic blooms of Pseudo-nitzschia spp. might be possible, especially because of the expected increase in nutrient availability from pollution and desert dust. Global warming may have an influence as well by lengthening the growth period for Pseudo-nitzschia, enlarging their global distribution and increasing the dust load through desertification. © 2001 Elsevier Science B.V.","Algal blooms; Amnesic shellfish poison; Coastal pollution; Desert dust; Diatom; Domoic acid; Pseudo-nitzschia","domoic acid; marine toxin; nitrogen; phosphorus; silicon; trace metal; article; desert; diatom; environmental factor; geographic distribution; greenhouse effect; marine environment; metal metabolism; nonhuman; priority journal; Pseudonitzschia; seashore; shellfish; temperature; water pollution; algae; Bacillariophyceae; Bacillariophyta; Nitzschia; Pseudo-nitzschia",,,,,,"Abboud-Abi Saab, M., Chedid, S., Kassab, M., Relationships between toxic phytoplankton and environmental factors in fishing harbors in Lebanese waters (2000) Proceedings of the Ninth Conference on Harmful Algal Blooms, , Tasmania, abstract; Ajani, P., Lee, R., Pritchard, T., Krogh, M., Phytoplankton dynamics at a long-term coastal station off Sydney, Australia (2000) Proceedings of the Ninth Conference on Harmful Algal Blooms, , Tasmania, abstract; Anderson, D.M., Red tides (1994) Scientific American, 271, pp. 62-69; Bates, S.S., Ecophysiology and metabolism of ASP toxin production (1998), pp. 405-426. , Anderson, D.M., Cembella, A.D., Hallegraeff, G.M. (Eds.), Physiological Ecology of Harmfull Algal Blooms. Springer-Verlag, HeidelbergBates, S.S., Bird, C.J., De Freitas, A.S.W., Foxall, R., Gilgan, M., Hanic, L.A., Johnson, G.R., Wright, J.L.C., Pennate diatom Niztschia pungens as the primary source of domoic acid, a toxin in shellfish from eastern Prince Edward Island, Canada (1989) Canadian Journal of Fisheries and Aquatic Science, 46, pp. 1203-1215; Bates, S.S., De Freitas, A.S.W., Milley, J.E., Pocklington, R., Quiliam, M.A., Smith, J.C., Worms, J., Controls on domoic acid production by the diatom Nitzschia pungens f. multiseries 